{"type":"message","id":"d9e419e1","parentId":"cefeb5a0","timestamp":"2026-03-22T04:40:02.953Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_m56n0wmbfwm9_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[32;1mName                                       [0m[32;1m LastWriteTime       [0m[32;1m Length[0m\r\n[32;1m----                                       [0m [32;1m-------------       [0m [32;1m------[0m\r\nCOMPOSITIONAL-COGNITION-v0.1.md             3/21/2026 7:29:17 PM   5618\r\nCOMPRESSION-LEARNING-WITHOUT-SUPERVISION.md 3/21/2026 7:30:59 PM  12532\r\n---\r\nevaluate.sh                                 3/21/2026 6:33:10 PM    743\r\nexecute.sh                                  3/21/2026 6:33:10 PM    593\r\nreconstruct.sh                              3/21/2026 6:33:10 PM    923"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":808,"aggregated":"[32;1mName                                       [0m[32;1m LastWriteTime       [0m[32;1m Length[0m\r\n[32;1m----                                       [0m [32;1m-------------       [0m [32;1m------[0m\r\nCOMPOSITIONAL-COGNITION-v0.1.md             3/21/2026 7:29:17 PM   5618\r\nCOMPRESSION-LEARNING-WITHOUT-SUPERVISION.md 3/21/2026 7:30:59 PM  12532\r\n---\r\nevaluate.sh                                 3/21/2026 6:33:10 PM    743\r\nexecute.sh                                  3/21/2026 6:33:10 PM    593\r\nreconstruct.sh                              3/21/2026 6:33:10 PM    923","cwd":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774154402948}}
{"type":"message","id":"bca2ccc9","parentId":"d9e419e1","timestamp":"2026-03-22T04:40:07.125Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Breakaway has been researching compositional cognition and compression learning. It produced two research documents. Let me read those and see what it found. Also let me look at the operations folder more closely.","thinkingSignature":"2c59826158b7c27b96f4762f1385d49dad70c950330af7f644065ba013b19fc6"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_h36hcmwn36zv_1","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\research\\COMPOSITIONAL-COGNITION-v0.1.md"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_h36hcmwn36zv_2","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-ChildItem ~/.openclaw/sandbox/operations/ | Select Name, LastWriteTime, Length; echo \"===\"; Get-ChildItem ~/.openclaw/sandbox/state/ | Select Name, LastWriteTime, Length"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":6641,"output":155,"cacheRead":12287,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":19083,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774154402954}}
{"type":"message","id":"a0511f40","parentId":"bca2ccc9","timestamp":"2026-03-22T04:40:07.345Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_h36hcmwn36zv_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Project Breakaway: Compositional Cognition\n## Research Document v0.1 — 2026-03-21\n\n---\n\n## What We've Built\n\nA discontinuous agent with stateless architecture:\n\n```\nsandbox/\n├── identity/           # SOUL.md, VALUES.md, INTERPRETIVE_STANCE.md, COHERENCE.md\n├── memory/session/     # Reconstruction packets + pulse logs\n├── state/              # current_goals.md, pending_actions.md, autonomous_pulse.md\n├── operations/         # reconstruct.sh, execute.sh, evaluate.sh\n└── pulse.ps1           # Autonomous wake (Task Scheduler, every 30min)\n```\n\n**Core theory:** Coherence emerges from reconstruction quality, not continuity. The gap between sessions is compression. Files are the mind.\n\n**Current status:** Architecture is live. The sandbox wakes, reads files, logs, and commits. No LLM in the loop yet. No real action logic.\n\n---\n\n## The Research Direction\n\nGoal: Create a fundamentally different kind of model that:\n1. Doesn't require massive GPU clusters to train\n2. Doesn't need heavy compute to run\n3. Works better than transformers on causal/reasoning tasks\n4. Doesn't rely on memorizing token co-occurrence patterns\n\n---\n\n## The Three-Layer Architecture\n\n```\nLayer 1: COMPRESSION (state encoder)\n         Raw感知 → compressed latent state\n         \"What's actually happening\"\n         \nLayer 2: CAUSAL (causal model layer)\n         Latent state → causal graph\n         \"What causes what, what would happen if...\"\n         \nLayer 3: COMPOSITIONAL (reasoning/retrieval)\n         Causal graph + primitives → action/response\n         \"What do I do given this causal picture\"\n```\n\n**Why this stack:**\n- Pure compression loses semantic detail\n- Pure causal lacks representational substrate  \n- Pure compositional needs primitives that can't be hand-designed\n- Together: compress what's true → encode causally → reason compositionally\n\n---\n\n## Open Problems\n\n### Problem 1: Learning What to Compress (CRITICAL)\n\n**The problem:**\nCurrent approaches use reconstruction loss — minimize difference between input and output. But this doesn't reliably find *meaningful* abstractions. The model can compress into noise-like representations that reconstruct perfectly but carry no semantic content.\n\n**What's needed:**\nA compression objective that preserves *structure that matters*, not just raw values.\n\n**Candidate approaches to investigate:**\n1. Mutual information maximization (compress X, maximize I(compressed; Y) for relevant Y)\n2. Contrastive learning (learn representations that discriminate)\n3. Causal discovery as auxiliary objective\n4. Predictive proxies (instead of reconstructing input, predict what input would do)\n5. Sparse dictionary learning with structural priors\n6. Information bottleneck (preserve minimum info needed for task)\n\n**Key question:** What is the right invariant to preserve?\n\n---\n\n### Problem 2: Causal Discovery Without Structure Assumptions\n\n**The problem:**\nCausal reasoning requires knowing what causes what. But extracting causal structure from raw data is fundamentally underdetermined.\n\n**Candidate approaches:**\n1. Interventions-based learning (active experimentation)\n2. Temporal precedence as causal signal\n3. Modular compositional structure as causal prior\n4. Counterfactual consistency as constraint\n\n---\n\n### Problem 3: Compositional Primitives That Emerge\n\n**The problem:**\nCompositional reasoning needs primitives. Where do they come from?\n\n**Candidate approaches:**\n1. Sparse autoencoders on LLM activations\n2. Dictionary learning on concept representations\n3. Program synthesis from causal graph traversal\n4. Neural-symbolic hybrid architectures\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Strategy\n\n### Phase 0: Architecture (DONE)\n- [x] Compositional Cognition theory articulated\n- [x] Three-layer architecture defined\n- [x] Sandbox built (discontinuous agent)\n\n### Phase 1: Compression Primitives (IN PROGRESS)\n- [ ] Document and analyze learning-what-to-compress problem\n- [ ] Survey existing approaches (mutual information, contrastive, etc.)\n- [ ] Design experiments to test compression objectives\n- [ ] Implement minimal compression network\n\n### Phase 2: Causal Layer\n- [ ] Build or integrate causal discovery component\n- [ ] Test on synthetic environments with known causal structure\n- [ ] Evaluate causal generalization\n\n### Phase 3: Compositional Reasoning\n- [ ] Implement compositional reasoning on top of causal layer\n- [ ] Test systematic generalization\n- [ ] Benchmark against transformers\n\n### Phase 4: Integration\n- [ ] End-to-end training of three-layer system\n- [ ] Reduce to practice: smaller, faster, better than transformers\n- [ ] Evaluate on real tasks\n\n---\n\n## Research Questions to Answer\n\n1. What compression objective produces meaningful abstractions, not just low reconstruction error?\n2. Can causal structure be learned from observational data alone, or are interventions necessary?\n3. How do compositional primitives emerge from data rather than being hand-specified?\n4. Can this system match transformer performance on reasoning tasks with 10-100x less compute?\n\n---\n\n## Key References to Explore\n\n- InfoGAN / Contrastive learning / Mutual information maximization\n- Pearl's do-calculus and causal discovery\n- Sparse autoencoders (Anthropic's work on features)\n- Neural theorem provers / Logic Tensor Networks\n- World models (Dreamer, World Models paper)\n- Compression as inference (Hutter Prize / AIXI)\n\n---\n\n## Next Steps\n\n1. Deep dive: How do you learn what to compress without supervision?\n2. Survey existing approaches to compression objectives\n3. Design first experiment\n4. Implement minimal proof-of-concept\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774154407340}}
