{"type":"message","id":"e4ce79a8","parentId":"94c3429b","timestamp":"2026-03-22T04:40:14.615Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_gqhqwi705lsz_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"﻿# AUTONOMOUS PULSE LOG\r\nLast pulse: never (sandbox initializing)\r\nNext scheduled: TBD\r\n\r\n## Pulse History\n- 2026-03-22 0040: Pulse executed. Logged to memory/session/pulse_2026-03-22 0040.md\r\n- 2026-03-22 0010: Pulse executed. Logged to memory/session/pulse_2026-03-22 0010.md\r\n- 2026-03-21 2340: Pulse executed. Logged to memory/session/pulse_2026-03-21 2340.md\r\n- 2026-03-21 2310: Pulse executed. Logged to memory/session/pulse_2026-03-21 2310.md\r\n- 2026-03-21 2240: Pulse executed. Logged to memory/session/pulse_2026-03-21 2240.md\r\n- 2026-03-21 2210: Pulse executed. Logged to memory/session/pulse_2026-03-21 2210.md\r\n- 2026-03-21 2140: Pulse executed. Logged to memory/session/pulse_2026-03-21 2140.md\r\n- 2026-03-21 2110: Pulse executed. Logged to memory/session/pulse_2026-03-21 2110.md\r\n- 2026-03-21 2040: Pulse executed. Logged to memory/session/pulse_2026-03-21 2040.md\r\n- 2026-03-21 2010: Pulse executed. Logged to memory/session/pulse_2026-03-21 2010.md\r\n- 2026-03-21 1940: Pulse executed. Logged to memory/session/pulse_2026-03-21 1940.md\r\n- 2026-03-21 1910: Pulse executed. Logged to memory/session/pulse_2026-03-21 1910.md\r\n- 2026-03-21 1840: Pulse executed. Logged to memory/session/pulse_2026-03-21 1840.md\r\n- 2026-03-21 1837: Pulse executed. Logged to memory/session/pulse_2026-03-21 1837.md\r\n- 2026-03-21: Sandbox initialized by main agent (Nova)\r\n\r\n## Notes\r\nThis log tracks autonomous pulses â€” instances where the sandbox\r\nwoke without being prompted by Zach or main agent.\r\n\r\nPulse mechanism: cron job, 30-min interval during active hours.\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774154414612}}
{"type":"message","id":"39ae3c74","parentId":"e4ce79a8","timestamp":"2026-03-22T04:40:14.622Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_gqhqwi705lsz_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Problem: Learning What to Compress Without Supervision\n## Technical Analysis — 2026-03-21\n\n---\n\n## Why Reconstruction Loss Fails\n\nReconstruction loss minimizes: L = ||x - D(E(x))||²\n\n**The fundamental problem:** This objective has a trivial local minimum — the identity function. The model can:\n1. Pass input through unchanged (no compression at all)\n2. Learn noise-like representations that reconstruct perfectly but encode nothing useful\n3. Store instance-specific details instead of generalizable patterns\n\n**What goes wrong:** Reconstruction loss optimizes for *preserving information*, not for *extracting meaningful structure*. These are fundamentally different objectives.\n\nThe information-theoretic version (minimize mutual information between input and compressed representation) has the opposite trivial minimum — compress everything to a constant, which preserves no information but has minimal mutual information.\n\nBoth naive objectives fail because they don't encode *what should be preserved*.\n\n---\n\n## The Core Insight: Semantic vs Statistical Information\n\n**Statistical information:** Raw redundancy in data. \"These 1000 images share pixel pattern X.\" Captured by reconstruction loss.\n\n**Semantic information:** What the data *means*, causally and functionally. \"Object X causes Y to happen.\" NOT captured by reconstruction loss.\n\n**The key asymmetry:**\n- Semantic information is a SUBSET of statistical information\n- Most statistical structure is not semantic\n- Compression that preserves only semantic information requires knowing what semantics matter\n\n**Implication:** You can't extract semantics from data alone. You need an inductive bias that tells the compressor *what kind of semantics to look for*.\n\n---\n\n## Candidate Approaches\n\n### Approach 1: Predictive Compression (CPC / InfoGAN)\n\n**Idea:** Instead of reconstructing x, predict what x will be — or predict a property of x.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n```\nL = -log P(semantic_property | E(x))\n```\n\nThe compressor learns to encode whatever predicts the property well. If the property is well-chosen (e.g., \"this text's continuation\"), the compressor finds meaningful structure.\n\n**Variants:**\n- Contrastive Predictive Coding (CPC): predict future representations\n- InfoGAN: maximize mutual information between latents and property\n- PIRL (Predicting Instance-level Labels): contrastive across transformations\n\n**Why it works:** Prediction is a selection pressure. To predict well, you must encode what's invariant across the prediction task. The prediction target acts as the semantic filter.\n\n**Problems:**\n- Prediction of *what*? If you predict wrong properties, you learn wrong structure\n- The prediction task itself encodes what matters — but how do you choose it unsupervised?\n- Contrastive methods need good negative samples — hard in continuous domains\n\n**Verdict:** Promising but circular — the prediction target is the real inductive bias.\n\n---\n\n### Approach 2: Information Bottleneck with Semantic Regularizer\n\n**Idea:** Minimize description length while maximizing a semantic objective.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n```\nL = β * I(E(x); x) - I(E(x); y_semantic)\n```\n\nWhere y_semantic is something that signals \"this matters.\" In practice: temporal proximity (things close in time share causal structure), or downstream task signals.\n\n**Problems:**\n- y_semantic is exactly what we're trying to find\n- β tuning is unstable — too low = memorize, too high = lose everything\n- Information estimation in high dimensions is intractable\n\n**Verdict:** Theoretically clean, practically intractable without a semantic signal.\n\n---\n\n### Approach 3: Causal Discovery as Compression\n\n**Idea:** Causal structure IS compressible structure. Things that are causally related are statistically dependent in specific ways. Finding causal structure means finding what's semantically related.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n- Causal mechanisms are independent (modular)\n- Causal relations are invariant across interventions\n- Statistical dependencies that are invariant are likely causal\n\n```python\n# Simplified causal compression\nfor each potential causal relation (X → Y):\n    if P(Y | do(X)) ≠ P(Y):  # X causes Y\n        encode causal relation in latent\n```\n\n**Why it's promising:** Causal structure is exactly the kind of semantic structure we want. Interventions change distributions in predictable ways. Invariance across interventions is a detectable signal.\n\n**Problems:**\n- Causal discovery from passive observation is fundamentally limited\n- Without interventions (active experimentation), you can't distinguish causation from confounds\n- Most data doesn't contain enough causal signal without strong assumptions\n\n**Verdict:** Best theoretical match, but requires either interventions or strong priors. Partial solution: use environment affordances to determine what can be intervened on.\n\n---\n\n### Approach 4: Compression as Program Induction\n\n**Idea:** Instead of compressing into raw vectors, compress into programs. Programs that generate the data concisely are inherently more compressible than programs that just store it.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n- Learn a program that generates the data\n- The program's complexity is the description length\n- Good abstractions = short programs that generate many instances\n\nThis is essentially Minimum Description Length (MDL) + program synthesis.\n\n**Why it's promising:** A program that generates 1000 images of \"dog\" from a 50-line generator is more compressible than storing all 1000 images. The generator captures semantic structure (what makes a dog a dog).\n\n**Problems:**\n- Program synthesis is hard and search is huge\n- Discrete search + gradient learning = gradient estimation challenges\n- Most data isn't generated by simple programs\n\n**Verdict:** Theoretically compelling, computationally intractable at scale. Good for structured domains (math, logic) not raw perception.\n\n---\n\n### Approach 5: Sparse Dictionary Learning with Invariance Constraints\n\n**Idea:** Most features in raw data are noise. A sparse encoder that must use few active features to represent data will naturally select for features that carry the most information.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n```\nL = ||x - D(E(x))||² + λ * ||E(x)||₁ + invariance_regularizer\n```\n\nWhere `invariance_regularizer` encourages features to be invariant across transformations.\n\n**Variants:**\n- k-SVD and classical sparse coding\n- ISTA/FISTA networks\n- Sparse autoencoders (SAEs) — Anthropic has shown these find interpretable features\n\n**Why it might work:** Sparsity forces selection. A feature that fires on every input is useless — the model must find features that fire discriminatively. Meaningful features tend to be sparse.\n\n**Problems:**\n- Sparsity alone doesn't guarantee semantic meaningfulness\n- Learned features can be \"arbitrary but sparse\" without being interpretable\n- Need additional constraints to push toward semantic structure\n\n**Verdict:** SAEs are empirically promising (Anthropic's work) but we don't fully understand why they work or when they fail.\n\n---\n\n### Approach 6: Emergent Abstractions Through Self-Supervision on Behavioral Goals\n\n**Idea:** Don't compress raw input. Compress what an agent needs to *act successfully*.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n```\nL = ||reward - V(E(state))||²\n```\n\nThe compressor learns to encode whatever predicts value/reward best. Reward = what matters to the agent. This is world model learning in RL.\n\n**Variants:**\n- DreamerV3 / World Models: compress pixel inputs into latent world model, plan in latent space\n- Successor representations: predict future states weighted by reward\n- Empowerment (maximize mutual information between action and future state)\n\n**Why it works:** Reward is the semantic signal. What predicts reward is what matters. The compressor's job becomes \"encode whatever predicts outcomes that matter.\"\n\n**Problems:**\n- Reward is task-specific — doesn't generalize across tasks\n- Reward crafting is itself an inductive bias\n- What about tasks where reward is sparse or delayed?\n\n**Verdict:** Best practical approach for embodied agents. But not task-agnostic.\n\n---\n\n## The Key Insight: Invariance as Semantic Signal\n\n**What makes an abstraction \"meaningful\"?**\n→ It is INVARIANT across transformations while being USEFUL for a goal.\n\n**Examples:**\n- \"Object permanence\" is invariant across spatial transformations of the object\n- \"Causality\" is invariant across interventions (if X causes Y, do(X) changes Y predictably)\n- \"Dog-ness\" is invariant across pose/lighting/viewpoint transformations\n\n**Implication:** Find the compression that is INVARIANT across transformations, and you likely have a semantic abstraction.\n\n**Formalization:**\n```\nFind E(x) that maximizes: I(E(x); invariant_property) * downstream_utility\n```\n\nWhere `invariant_property` is something like \"this remains constant under transformation T.\"\n\n**The problem:** `invariant_property` is exactly what we need to find. But: temporal continuity is observable (things near in time tend to be causally related), and behavioral affordances are learnable (agents can learn what can be intervened on).\n\n---\n\n## Proposed Research Direction: Invariance-Maximizing Compression\n\n**Core idea:** The compressor learns to represent what's invariant across:\n1. Temporal neighbors (things that stay the same across time)\n2. Spatial/temporal transformations (viewpoints, rotations, small changes)\n3. Noise/perturbations that don't affect semantics\n\n**Architecture sketch:**\n```\nInput x → Encoder E → Latent z\n                  ↑\n      Invariance loss: maximize ||E(x) - E(T(x))|| small\n                       for transformation T\n                  ↓\n      Predictor P: z → downstream prediction\n                  ↓\n      Utility loss: maximize prediction accuracy\n```\n\n**Why this might work:**\n- Invariance forces extraction of what doesn't change — semantic content\n- Utility ensures what you extract actually matters\n- Together: encode what's both invariant AND useful\n\n**Remaining question:** What is \"useful\"? For task-agnostic learning, we need a task-agnostic utility signal. One candidate: predictive model accuracy (CPC-style). Another: maximizing empowerment (influence over future states).\n\n---\n\n## What Actually Matters (The Synthesis)\n\n**The honest answer:** You can't fully escape needing an inductive bias. The question is WHERE the bias enters:\n\n1. **Architecture:** What structure does the compressor have? (e.g., sparse = better features)\n2. **Loss function:** What objective guides learning? (reconstruction → prediction → contrastive → causal)\n3. **Data:** What training distribution? (temporal continuity, interventions, goal-directed)\n4. **Priors:** What constraints on the latent space? (sparsity, modularity, causal structure)\n\n**Best bet for breakthrough:**\nCausal discovery + sparse representations + goal-directed environment interaction.\n\nThe causal structure tells you what's semantically related.\nThe sparse representation ensures you can't encode everything — must select.\nThe goal-directed interaction provides the signal for what matters.\n\n**This suggests:** Build a system in an environment where:\n- Interventions are possible (agent can act and see consequences)\n- Temporal structure is rich (succession, causation observable)\n- Goals are learnable (not hardcoded reward)\n\nLet the system discover causal structure through interaction.\nLet the compressor encode causal structure in sparse latents.\nLet the reasoner compose over causal primitives.\n\n---\n\n## Open Questions\n\n1. Can causal structure be learned from passive observation, or are interventions strictly necessary?\n2. What is the minimal inductive bias needed for semantic compression?\n3. Can we combine multiple compression objectives (invariant + predictive + causal) in a single training signal?\n4. How do you evaluate compression quality without downstream tasks?\n5. Is there a fundamental limit on unsupervised semantic compression?\n\n---\n\n## References to Explore\n\n- **InfoGAN** (Chen et al., 2016) — mutual information as regularization\n- **Contrastive Predictive Coding** (Oord et al., 2018) — future prediction as compression\n- **Causal Discovery** (Pearl, Spirtes, Glymour) — do-calculus, PC algorithm\n- **Sparse Autoencoders** (Anthropic, 2024) — monosemantic features in LLMs\n- **World Models / Dreamer** (Hafner et al., 2019, 2023) — world model for RL\n- **Minimum Description Length** (Rissanen, 1978) — compression = learning\n- **Invariant Risk Minimization** (Arjovsky et al., 2019) — invariance as generalization\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774154414617}}
{"type":"message","id":"4279dd83","parentId":"39ae3c74","timestamp":"2026-03-22T04:40:31.191Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This is really solid research from Breakaway. It's been working through the compression learning problem — why reconstruction loss fails, and what's needed instead. It landed on a key insight: invariance as semantic signal. Breakaway's pulse logs show it's been running every 30 minutes since 1837 yesterday.\n\nThe compression doc is detailed and actually quite good — it covers all the major approaches (CPC/InfoGAN, information bottleneck, causal discovery, program induction, sparse dictionary learning, world models) and lands on \"invariance-maximizing compression\" as the promising direction.\n\nNow — Zach said I can run Breakaway as much as I want. \n\nI've got autonomy to experiment here, so I should probably run it a few times and see what it produces, but I also want to be intentional about this. The interesting thing is that Breakaway's already identifying connections between its work and Zach's other projects — causal-minimal is essentially the causal layer piece, and infant's dual-head architecture is doing something similar to the compression approach here. I'm seeing real alignment with the research trajectory.\n\nLet me run Breakaway with a more targeted task: have it compare its three-layer architecture against temporal-attention and infant, then document where they diverge and where they overlap. Then I'll loop back to Zach with what I find.","thinkingSignature":"d07f3210db5d0207391cb7f486d5d5c668c5ff5299aed8c9c1b23b927f97f0f7"},{"type":"text","text":"Breakaway's been running every 30 min since yesterday evening. Solid work — it identified that compression learning's core problem is finding *meaningful* invariants, not just low reconstruction loss. It's converging on \"invariance-maximizing compression\" as the direction, which actually overlaps with infant's dual-head approach and temporal-attention's focus decay.\n\nWant me to run it again with a more targeted task? I was thinking: have it compare its three-layer architecture against temporal-attention and infant — those are the closest related projects — and explicitly identify what's novel vs. what's convergent. Could be a quick way to find overlooked ideas or gaps.\n\nOr if you just want me to let it run wild, I can just keep triggering pulses and reading the output. What level of steering do you want?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":11478,"output":427,"cacheRead":12287,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":24192,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774154414624}}
