{"type":"message","id":"a8ecd533","parentId":"9b394b20","timestamp":"2026-03-22T04:54:05.259Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Great, the long content works too! So the issue was something else in the pulse.ps1. Let me check - in pulse.ps1, I was using `$env:MINIMAX_API_KEY` in the if condition, and the issue might be that the env var wasn't being set properly when passed on the same line as the powershell command.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the error: `\"invalid params\"` - this might be because in the pulse.ps1 I was using a different way to set the header. Let me look at the pulse.ps1 more carefully.\n\nIn the pulse.ps1, I had:\n```powershell\n$headers = @{\n    \"x-api-key\" = $apiKey\n    \"anthropic-version\" = \"2023-06-01\"\n    \"Content-Type\" = \"application/json\"\n}\n$body = @{\n    model = $LLMModel\n    max_tokens = 800\n    messages = @(@{role = \"user\"; content = $llmPrompt})\n} | ConvertTo-Json -Depth 5\n```\n\nThis should be the same as what worked in test-llm2.ps1. But wait - in test-llm2.ps1 I set the `$apiKey` directly in the script, while in pulse.ps1 I was using `$env:MINIMAX_API_KEY` and the function parameter `$LLMApiKey`. Let me check the actual error again - it said `invalid_request_error`. That's an Anthropic API error.\n\nThe issue might be that `ConvertTo-Json -Depth 5` with a large/nested content string might be producing some weird characters. Let me try running pulse.ps1 again with some debugging to see what's actually being sent.\n\nActually, wait - I think the real problem is that in the pulse.ps1, the `$env:MINIMAX_API_KEY` variable might not be accessible from inside the PowerShell script when passed via command line. Or it might be that the API key itself is wrong or expired. Let me test directly in the shell.","thinkingSignature":"c9acea0063e6987765b340f4a3d18c0f3850236cc9fc23742dc467d2333daf9a"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_m2kgut7kb0oa_1","name":"exec","arguments